<h2>FAQ</h2>
<p><strong>How long does it take to increase organic traffic?</strong></p>
<p>Low-competition keywords can rank within 30 to 60 days. Medium-competition keywords take 3 to 6 months. Building significant organic traffic (10,000+ monthly visits) from a new site typically takes 6 to 12 months of consistent publishing. The compounding effect means growth accelerates over time.</p>
<p><strong>How many blog posts do I need to increase organic traffic?</strong></p>
<p>Companies publishing 16+ posts per month see 3.5 times more traffic than those publishing 0 to 4. Start with 4 posts per month minimum. Each post should target a specific keyword and be part of a content cluster. Volume without strategy does not produce results.</p>
<p><strong>Why is my organic traffic dropping?</strong></p>
<p>Common causes include Google algorithm updates, technical SEO issues (crawl errors, slow speed), content decay (outdated information), lost backlinks, increased competition, and the rise of zero-click searches. Check Google Search Console for specific page-level drops and correlate with update timelines.</p>
<p><strong>Does social media increase organic traffic?</strong></p>
<p>Social media does not directly affect Google rankings. Social shares do not count as backlinks. But social media drives referral traffic, increases brand awareness, and can lead to natural backlinks when people discover and reference your content. <a href="/blog/repurpose-blog-content-social-media/">Repurposing blog content for social media</a> amplifies your reach without creating new content.</p>
<p><strong>What is a good organic traffic growth rate?</strong></p>
<p>10 to 20% month-over-month growth is strong for sites in the first 12 months. Established sites targeting 5 to 10% monthly growth are on track. Any consistent growth is better than stagnation. Measure growth against your own baseline, not competitors.</p>
